{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645100"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:13:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:13:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18086"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18086"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.71,0.1,0.1,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10800"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75893"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10800"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18086"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61406"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5760"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25154"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25978"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75893"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMedical negligence claims in Australia are governed by both common law principles and state-based Civil Liability Acts. These laws allow patients to seek compensation when they have been harmed by substandard medical care.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the essential elements required to establish medical negligence in Australia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Professional misconduct and patient dissatisfaction","Duty of care, breach of duty, causation, and harm","Poor documentation and adverse outcome","Intent to harm, breach of contract, and damages","Medical error, patient complaint, and compensation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETo establish medical negligence in Australia, four essential elements must be proven: \u003Cstrong\u003Eduty of care, breach of duty, causation, and harm\u003C/strong\u003E. A duty of care exists when a doctor-patient relationship is established. Breach occurs when care falls below the standard expected according to peer professional opinion. Causation links the breach to the harm suffered. The patient suffered a quantifiable harm, such as physical injury, psychological harm, or financial loss, as a result of the breach of duty.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProfessional misconduct and patient dissatisfaction\u003C/strong\u003E are matters that may be dealt with by the Australian Health Practitioner Regulation Agency (AHPRA) but are not sufficient legal elements to establish negligence\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPoor documentation and adverse outcome\u003C/strong\u003E may support a negligence claim but are not the essential legal elements required under Australian law\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntent to harm, breach of contract, and damages\u003C/strong\u003E includes elements more relevant to criminal cases or contract law, whereas negligence in Australia does not require proof of intent\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedical error, patient complaint, and compensation\u003C/strong\u003E may be present in negligence cases but do not align with the specific legal elements required by Australian courts\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnder section 5O of the Civil Liability Act, the standard of care is determined by peer professional opinion widely accepted as competent professional practice, unless the court considers that opinion to be irrational.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Medical negligence in Australia requires four elements: duty of care, breach of duty, causation, and harm/damages.","The standard of care in Australian law is determined by peer professional opinion that is widely accepted as competent professional practice.","The Civil Liability Acts in Australian states codify negligence law and modify common law principles."],"references":["Cheluvappa R, Selvendran S. Medical negligence - Key cases and application of legislation. Ann Med Surg (Lond). 2020;57:205-211. Published 2020 Jul 17. doi:10.1016/j.amsu.2020.07.017"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61406"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18086"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61406"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T12:29:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T12:30:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10800"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75893"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships"